\section{Metallic $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ monolayer as an anode material for $\mathrm{Li}$, $\mathrm{Na}, \mathrm{K}, \mathrm{Mg}$ or $\mathrm{Ca}$ ion storage: a first-principle study}
Using density functional theory (DFT), we assess the suitability of monolayer $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ as promising electrode materials for $\mathrm{Li}, \mathrm{Na}, \mathrm{K}, \mathrm{Mg}$ and $\mathrm{Ca}$ ion batteries. The metallic $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ monolayer can offer an intrinsic advantage for the transportation of electrons in materials. The results suggest that $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ can provide excellent mobility with lower diffusion barriers of $0.043 \mathrm{eV}$ for $\mathrm{K}, 0.119 \mathrm{eV}$ for Li, $0.098 \mathrm{eV}$ for $\mathrm{Na}$, $0.517 \mathrm{eV}$ for $\mathrm{Mg}$, and $0.306 \mathrm{eV}$ for $\mathrm{Ca}$. The specific capacities of $\mathrm{Li}, \mathrm{Na}$ and $\mathrm{Mg}$ can reach up to 968,613 and $815 \mathrm{~mA} \mathrm{~h} \mathrm{~g}^{-1}$ respectively, which are significantly larger than the corresponding value of graphite. Herein, with high open-circuit voltage the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet could be a promising candidate for the anode material in battery applications.

\section{Introduction}
The increase of the energy demands and the concentration of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere signify the search for sustainable and renewable energy sources. Li-ion battery (LIB) is an attractive power source and has been widely applied in portable electronic devices and electric vehicles. ${ }^{1-7}$ However, several issues including cost, safety, and capacity restrict the further development in large scale energy storage applications of LIB. ${ }^{8,9}$ Therefore, the development of new types of batteries is urgently needed. Batteries based on alternative carrier ions, such as $\mathrm{Na},{ }^{10-13} \mathrm{~K}^{14,15} \mathrm{Mg}^{16,17}$ or $\mathrm{Ca},{ }^{17}$ may be more suitable for large-scale energy storage systems. It is well known that the performance of ion batteries relies greatly on the properties of electrode materials. Therefore, great effort is being expended on finding novel and efficient electrode materials for next generation of renewable energy technologies. So far, two-dimensional (2D) materials, such as graphene ${ }^{18}$ porous graphene, ${ }^{19}$ silicene, $^{20}$ transition-metal dichalcogenides (TMDS), ${ }^{21-24}$ MXenes, ${ }^{25}$ black phosphorus ${ }^{26,27}$ and borophene, ${ }^{6,28-30}$ have been widely studied because of their particular structural, physical, and chemical properties, which may enable the high capacity and the fast metal ion diffusivity.

Recently, a new 2D material, namely vanadium dioxide $\left(\mathrm{VO}_{2}\right)$ has attracted great attention owing to its semiconductor to

