\section{Computational method}
First-principles density functional theory (DFT) calculations in the present study were carried out using Vienna $a b$ initio simulation package (VASP) ${ }^{36-38}$ with a generalized gradient approximation (GGA) in the Perdew-Burke-Ernzerhof (PBE).$^{39}$ Since the van der Waals (vdW) interaction plays a crucial role in the adsorption of adatoms on the substrate, a non-local vdW density functional in the form of Becke88 optimization (optB88) ${ }^{40}$ is adopted, which has been evidenced to give a much improved description for various systems including heterostructures, ${ }^{41-43}$ lithium carbides ${ }^{44}$ and the molecules/2D materials systems. ${ }^{45,46} \mathrm{~A}$ kinetic energy cutoff of the plane-wave basis set was used to be $500 \mathrm{eV}$. A $k$-point sampling of $5 \times 5 \times 1$ Monkhorst-Pack grids ${ }^{47}$ in the first Brillouin zone of the $4 \times 4$ supercell is used in the calculation. An inter-layer vacuum space larger than $20 \AA$ was kept to avoid mirror interactions. The convergence criteria of total energy and Hellmann-Feynman force were set as $10^{-4} \mathrm{eV}$ and $0.01 \mathrm{eV} \AA^{-1}$, respectively. The optimized lattice constant of unit cell is $2.75 \AA$, the bond length of $\mathrm{V}-\mathrm{O}$ is $1.95 \AA$, which are consistent with previous results. ${ }^{35}$ For the evaluation of charge transfer between the ions and the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$, we performed Bader charge analysis. ${ }^{48}$ To obtain diffusion pathways and the corresponding energy barriers, we performed standard nudged elastic band (NEB) calculations. ${ }^{49}$

\section{Results and discussion}
3.1 Structures and electronic properties of metal adatoms adsorption on $\mathbf{V O}_{2}$ monolayer

The geometric structure of monolayer $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet is depicted in Fig. 1. Clearly, from the top view, the $\operatorname{VO}_{2}$ sheet exhibits typical graphene-like hexagonal structure, and from the side view, the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet is a triple-layer structure, which can be viewed as the $\mathrm{V}$-atomic layer being sandwiched by two O-atomic layers through strong $\mathrm{V}-\mathrm{O}$ bonds. The unit cell of monolayer $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet consists of two $\mathrm{O}$ atoms and one $\mathrm{V}$ atom. The optimized lattice constant and the bond length of $\mathrm{V}-\mathrm{O}$ are $2.753 \AA$ and $2.050 \AA$ respectively, which agree with the previous results. ${ }^{50}$ As depicted in Fig. 1 (b), $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ exhibits metallic behavior, which can ensure a satisfied electrical conductivity during battery cycling.

We first examine the adsorption behavior of a single metal atom $\left(\mathrm{Li}, \mathrm{Na}, \mathrm{K}, \mathrm{Mg}\right.$ and $\mathrm{Ca}$ ) on the monolayer $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$. The adsorption energy is defined as the difference between the sum of the energies of the pristine $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet and the metal atom and the total energy of the metal-adsorbed system:

\[
E_{\mathrm{a}}=E_{\mathrm{M}}+E_{\mathrm{VO}_{2}}-E_{\mathrm{M}_{\mathrm{MO}}^{2}}
\]

where $E_{\mathrm{M}}, E_{\mathrm{VO}_{2}}$, and $E_{\mathrm{M}_{1} \mathrm{VO}_{2}}$ are the energies of the metal adatoms, $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet and the metal atom adsorption on $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet. By this definition, the larger $E_{\mathrm{a}}$, the stronger the interaction between the metal adatom and the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet. It is well known that for a material to be suitable as an anode for a particular ion storage, a relatively large adsorption energy plays a fundamental role. The $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ with a $4 \times 4$ supercell structure is employed to avoid the interaction between the adjacent metal adatoms. We first determined the most favorable adsorption site for a single metal atom on $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet. Herein, four different initial adsorption sites are considered: above the hollow center of hexagonal V-O ring $(\mathrm{H})$, above the top of $\mathrm{O}$ atom (T1), above the top of $\mathrm{V}$ atom (T2) and above the V-O bond (B) as shown in Fig. 1(a). The results suggest that all the above metal atoms prefer to be adsorbed above the $\mathrm{H}$ site. The corresponding adsorption energies are $3.85,3.89,4.42,4.31$, and $6.21 \mathrm{eV}$ for $\mathrm{Li}$, $\mathrm{Na}, \mathrm{K}, \mathrm{Mg}$ and Ca respectively. These large adsorption energies ensure that the metal atoms can bind strongly to the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet.

To obtain insight into the adsorption process, we investigated the charge transfers by performing Bader charge analysis. ${ }^{48}$ The three-dimensional charge density difference of metal/ $/ \mathrm{VO}_{2}$ are illustrated in Fig. 2, which were obtained from the formula

\[
\Delta \rho=\rho\left(\text { metal } / \mathrm{VO}_{2}\right)-\left[\rho\left(\mathrm{VO}_{2}\right)+\rho(\text { metal })\right]
\]

where $\rho\left(\mathrm{metal} / \mathrm{VO}_{2}\right)$ and $\rho\left(\mathrm{VO}_{2}\right)$ denote the total electron densities of the relaxed $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet with and without metal atoms, respectively, and $\rho$ (metal) is the total electron density of the metal atoms. The red and blue colors represent charge accumulation and depletion. It is found that all the metal atoms behave as charge donors. They donate $0.91 e, 0.90 e, 0.94 e, 1.70 e$, and 1.64e to the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet for $\mathrm{Li}, \mathrm{Na}, \mathrm{K}, \mathrm{Mg}$ and Ca respectively. To further understand the interaction between the metal atom and the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet, we have calculated the partial density of states (PDOS) of different systems and illustrated them in Fig. 3. Unlike many other two-dimensional materials that exhibit semi-conducting or semi-metallic characteristics, the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet as well as all the metal $/ \mathrm{NO}_{2}$ systems are all metallic states. Therefore, the metallic nature of the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet remains unchanged during the metal adsorbed on it, and an excellent electronic conductivity is maintained, which will significantly improve the performance of metal ion batteries. The metal atoms donate their electrons to the $\mathrm{O}$ atoms of the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ so that the s and p orbitals of the Li, Na, $\mathrm{K}$ and $\mathrm{Mg}$ (s and $\mathrm{d}$ orbitals for Ca) partially appear above the Fermi level. Meanwhile, the orbital hybridization between the metal atoms and the $\mathrm{O}$ atoms are observed at the lower energy region, which contributes to the strong interaction between the metal atoms and the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$.

