atoms on the electrode material. From this point of view, the diffusion of metal atoms on the surface of $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ must be quantified. In this regard we investigate the diffusion barriers of metal atoms on the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet. As illustrated in Fig. 4(a), HT2-H pathway is the most favorable diffusion pathway for all metal atoms studied in this work. The corresponding diffusion energy profiles along the optimized pathway for different metal atoms are shown in Fig. 4(b). It is found that the diffusion barriers of the alkali atoms are lower than those of alkaline earth atoms. Among the three alkali atoms, K possesses the lowest diffusion barrier, with a value of $0.043 \mathrm{eV}$. The diffusion barriers of the Li and $\mathrm{Na}$ are $0.119 \mathrm{eV}$ and $0.098 \mathrm{eV}$, respectively. The obtained low barrier for alkaline atoms on $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ is far superior to typical electrode materials, such as $\mathrm{VS}_{2}(0.22 \mathrm{eV}){ }^{24}$ borophene $(0.60 \mathrm{eV}),{ }^{51}$ porous graphene $(0.37 \mathrm{eV}),{ }^{19} \mathrm{MoN}_{2}(0.49 \mathrm{eV}){ }^{14}$ and so on. ${ }^{52-54}$ The low diffusion barriers of alkaline atoms on $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ implies the fast diffusion processes, especially for $\mathrm{K}$ ion. On the other hand, we find that the obtained diffusion barriers of $\mathrm{Mg}$ and Ca are $0.517 \mathrm{eV}$ and $0.306 \mathrm{eV}$ respectively, which are comparable to the energy barriers for Li diffusion on other anode materials. ${ }^{51,53,55}$ Therefore, we can conclude that the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ monolayer will be easy for the above metal atoms to diffuse. In addition, the ZPE contributions are also considered. As a prototype model system, Li diffusion on $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ is tested. The diffusion barrier of $\mathrm{Li}$ on $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ with ZPE is $0.149 \mathrm{eV}$, which is slightly larger than that of the value $0.119 \mathrm{eV}$ calculated without ZPE. Although the NEB method without ZPE underestimates the diffusion barrier, it is still comparable to that calculated with ZPE.

