\subsection{Theoretical storage capacity of $\mathrm{Li}, \mathrm{Na}, \mathrm{K}, \mathrm{Mg}$ and $\mathrm{Ca}$ on the $\operatorname{VO}_{2}$ monolayer and open-circuit voltage}
Next, we increased the coverage of adatoms over the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet. To this aim, we constructed a series of configurations with the chemical stoichiometry of $\mathrm{M}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}(x=0.0625,0.25,0.5,0.75$, 1, $2,4)$ by placing different number of metal atoms on the single and both sides of the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet until the complete coverage was achieved. As a prototype model system, Fig. 5 displays the optimized structures for $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$ with $x$ varying from $0.0625$ to 4 . In the case of $\mathrm{M}_{2} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$, the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ fully covered by metal atoms leads to $x$ being 2 as illustrated in Fig. 5(f). In the case of $\mathrm{K}_{0.75} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$ and $\mathrm{Ca}_{0.75} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$, the average adsorption energies were estimated to be negative, this indicates that when the number of adsorbed of $K$ and $\mathrm{Ca}$ atoms is larger than $0.75$ in a unit cell, the systems are unstable. To test the feasibility of multilayer adsorption, we also studied the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ with bilayer metal atoms adsorbing on its both sides. For adsorption of the second layer, it should be noted that once the adsorption sites for the first layer are fully occupied, subsequent metal atoms of the next layer will occupy T2 sites. In the case of $\mathrm{Mg}_{4} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$, the average adsorption energy is calculated to be negative. This indicates that the second layer of $\mathrm{Mg}$ atoms can not be adsorbed on the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ with one layer of $\mathrm{Mg}$ atoms fully covering on both sides, because the extra atoms occupy a second layer and it is difficult for these atoms to be adsorbed on $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet. Interestingly, bilayer $\mathrm{Li}$ and Na adsorptions on both sides of $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet are feasible, corresponding to formulae of $\mathrm{M}_{4} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$, as shown in Fig. $5(\mathrm{~g})$. Open-circuit voltage date is another crucial parameter to characterize the performance of metal ion batteries. In theory, the open-circuit voltage for the metal atom coverages between $x_{1} \leq x \leq x_{2}$ can be obtained by using the following equation: ${ }^{24,56-58}$

\[
V \approx-\left(E_{\mathrm{M} x_{2} \mathrm{VO}_{2}}-E_{\mathrm{M} x_{1} \mathrm{VO}_{2}}-\left(x_{1}-x_{2}\right) E_{\mathrm{M}}\right) /\left(\left(x_{1}-x_{2}\right)\right)
\]

in which, $E_{\mathrm{Mx}_{2} \mathrm{VO}_{2}}, E_{\mathrm{M} x_{1} \mathrm{VO}_{2}}$, and $E_{\mathrm{M}}$ are the energies of $\mathrm{M}_{x_{2}} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$, $\mathrm{M}_{x_{1}} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$ and metal atom, respectively. Fig. 6 shows the voltage profiles of the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet as a function of the metal atom coverage ratio. It is seen that the voltage profiles of $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$ and $\mathrm{Na}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$ are all positive which additionally confirms the suitability of $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ as anode material. In the case of $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$, there is a dramatic decrease from approximately $3.85 \mathrm{~V}$ when $x<0.25$ to $2.08 \mathrm{~V}(x<0.75)$, and then decreases again to $1.16 \mathrm{~V}$. Next, the voltage values are fluctuating around $1.16 \mathrm{~V}(0.5<x<2)$. At last, the voltage value reduces to $0.31 \mathrm{~V}$ for the bilayer Li atoms adsorbed on both sides of the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$. The voltage profile of $\mathrm{Na}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$ is similar to that of $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$. In the case of $\mathrm{K}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$ $\left(\mathrm{Ca}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}\right)$, when the $\mathrm{K}(\mathrm{Ca})$ atom coverage ratio is larger than $0.75 \mathrm{~V}$, the open-circuit voltage becomes to be negative indicating that the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ as $\mathrm{K}(\mathrm{Ca})$ ion battery node material is unstable for high coverage ratio of $\mathrm{K}(\mathrm{Ca})$. In the case of $\mathrm{Mg}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$, when the $\mathrm{Mg}$ atom coverage ratio is lower than 2, the $\mathrm{Mg}_{x} \mathrm{VO} \mathrm{O}_{2}$ is stable. Meanwhile, we calculated the average open-circuit voltage by numerically averaging the voltage profile, which are $1.56 \mathrm{~V}$ for Li $(0<x<4), 0.98 \mathrm{~V}$ for $\mathrm{Na}(0<x<4), 2.36 \mathrm{~V}$ for $\mathrm{K}(0<x$ $<0.75), 1.21 \mathrm{~V}$ for $\mathrm{Mg}(0<x<1)$, and $2.82 \mathrm{~V}$ for $\mathrm{Ca}(0<x<0.75)$. Thus, the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ based metal ion battery can provide high charging voltage, which are proper for the practical anodic applications. ${ }^{57-59}$

To designate $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ monolayer as anode material for metal ion battery, we calculated the specific capacities using the following equation ${ }^{54,58,60}$

\[
C=\frac{n N_{\mathrm{A}} e}{3.6 m_{\mathrm{M}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}}}
\]

