in which $n$ is the adsorbed electric charge per mole $\mathrm{VO}_{2}, N_{\mathrm{A}}$ is the Avogadro constant, $e$ is the elementary charge, and $m_{\mathrm{M}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}}$ represents the molar mass of $\mathrm{M}_{x} \mathrm{VO}_{2}$. For bilayer $\mathrm{Li}$ or $\mathrm{Na}$ adsorption on both sides of the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet, each formula unit of $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet can accommodate up to $4 \mathrm{Li}$ or $4 \mathrm{Na}$ atoms. Corresponding theoretical capacities are found to be about 968 and $613 \mathrm{~mA} \mathrm{~h} \mathrm{~g}^{-1}$, respectively, which are much larger than that for most of 2D materials. For example, the theoretical capacity of $\mathrm{Li}$ on graphene is $372 \mathrm{~mA} \mathrm{~h} \mathrm{~g}^{-1}$, Li and $\mathrm{Na}$ on $\mathrm{Sc}_{2} \mathrm{C}$ are 462 and $362 \mathrm{~mA} \mathrm{~h} \mathrm{~g}^{-1},{ }^{58} \mathrm{Li}$ and $\mathrm{Na}$ on $\mathrm{Mo}_{2} \mathrm{C}$ are 526 and $132 \mathrm{~mA} \mathrm{~h} \mathrm{~g}^{-1},{ }^{60}$ and $\mathrm{Li}$ and $\mathrm{Na}$ on $\mathrm{Mo}_{2} \mathrm{~N}$ are 432 and $864 \mathrm{~mA} \mathrm{~h} \mathrm{~g}^{-1} \cdot{ }^{14}$ The maximum $\mathrm{Mg}$ content is 1 resulting the theoretical capacity of $815 \mathrm{~mA} \mathrm{~h} \mathrm{~g}^{-1}$, which is also higher than conventional electrode capacity. Regarding to $\mathrm{K}$ and $\mathrm{Ca}$ ions, the predicted capacities are 131 and $260 \mathrm{~mA} \mathrm{~h} \mathrm{~g}^{-1}$ respectively, which are distinctly lower than that for $\mathrm{Li}, \mathrm{Na}$ and $\mathrm{Mg}$. On the basis of the above analyses, we can conclude that the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ monolayer should be a good candidate for the application of an electrode material in metal ion batteries, especially for $\mathrm{Li}, \mathrm{Na}$ and $\mathrm{Mg}$ ion batteries. Also, it is equally important to explore the properties of the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ with the substrate it was formed on in the future.

\section{Conclusion}
In summary, we have demonstrated the application of the monolayer $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ as anode material for metal (Li, $\mathrm{Na}, \mathrm{K}, \mathrm{Mg}$ and Ca) ion batteries by DFT-based first-principles calculations. The results shown that the metal adatoms prefer to occupy the center of hexagonal $\mathrm{V}-\mathrm{O}$ ring and play the role of charge donors. The atoms adsorption on $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ exhibit the diffusion barriers as low as $0.043 \mathrm{eV}$ for $\mathrm{K}, 0.119 \mathrm{eV}$ for $\mathrm{Li}, 0.098 \mathrm{eV}$ for $\mathrm{Na}, 0.517 \mathrm{eV}$ for $\mathrm{Mg}$, and $0.306 \mathrm{eV}$ for $\mathrm{Ca}$, suggesting fast charging/ discharging processes especially for $\mathrm{K}, \mathrm{Li}$ and $\mathrm{Na}$. The metallic nature of the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ sheet remains unchanged during the metal adsorbed on it, which is essential for the use as an electrode. In addition, the theoretical specific capacity of $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ can be as much as 968,613 and $815 \mathrm{~mA} \mathrm{~h} \mathrm{~g}^{-1}$ for $\mathrm{Li}, \mathrm{Na}$ and $\mathrm{Mg}$ respectively, which are significantly larger than that of graphene. The results also shown that the $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ based metal ion battery can provide high charging voltage. Given these advantages, we can conclude that the monolayer $\mathrm{VO}_{2}$ has fascinating potential as the high capacity and fast charging-discharging anode material for metal ion batteries.

